50|$|The {{level of}} ACT {{was linked to}} the <b>basic</b> rate of <b>income</b> tax between 1973 and 1993. The March 1993 Budget of Norman Lamont cut the ACT rate and tax credit to 22.5% from April 1993, and 20% from April 1994. These changes were {{accompanied}} with a cut of income tax on dividends to 20%, while the <b>basic</b> rate of <b>income</b> tax remained at 25%. Persons liable for tax were lightly affected by the change, because income tax liability was still balanced by the tax credit received, although higher rate tax payers paid an additional 25% tax on the amount of the dividend actually received (net), as against 20% before the change.|$|R
40|$|Conference on Financing Global AgingThe {{question}} assigned {{is whether}} {{an aging population}} should be financed by governments or markets? The broad answer {{is that we need}} both government provided benefits and supplementary private pensions. Each has its place. That is not the debate. The debate centers on whether to cut back on the existing Social Security program and to replace it with private accounts. I think that is a bad idea. It is a bad idea because it shifts the nature of <b>basic</b> retirement <b>income</b> from a defined benefit to a defined contribution plan, which puts people’s <b>basic</b> retirement <b>income</b> at risk. Moreover, “privatizing ” will not, in and of itself, improve the financing of the system or raise the return on Social Security contributions. Improving the system’s finances and diversifying investments for a higher return are laudable goals, but they can be accomplished within the existing structure. I. Private Accounts on Their Own Do Not Help Financing Proponents of privatization rarely articulate how shifting responsibilities from the government to the private sector will contribute to Social Security finances. Restoring balance to a system where expenditures are projected to exceed revenues require...|$|R
